comments.body:
@chucklu Framework ResGen.exe and our ResGen is different tools. Our ResGen was temporary created for the repo to _only_ build PowerShell because .Net Core doesn't support _strong type based_ resources. 

If you want work with classic resources you should use `dotnet` command -  it will compile your resource files. I don't know if .Net Core support embed resources.

In any case your question is out of the repo.

@iSazonov  Do you know how to add a environment path to current session? (like the import-module function in powershell)
I am not sure where the ResGen.exe and al.exe will locate,

In batch script, I import the environment path temporarily

> SET P1=C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio 8\SmartDevices\SDK\SDKTools;
> SET P2=C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v2.0.50727;C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework64\v2.0.50727;
> SET P3=C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v4.0.30319;C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework64\v4.0.30319;
> SET P4=C:\Program Files\Microsoft.NET\SDK\v2.0 64bit\Bin;
> SET P5=C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v7.0A\Bin;
> SET P6=C:\Program Files\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v7.0A\bin;
> SET P7=C:\Program Files\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v7.1\Bin;
> SET P8=C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v8.1A\bin\NETFX 4.5.1 Tools;
> SET P9=C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v10.0A\bin\NETFX 4.6 Tools;
> SET P10=C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v10.0A\bin\NETFX 4.6.1 Tools;
> SET P11=C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft SDKs\Windows\v10.0A\bin\NETFX 4.6.2 Tools;
> 
> PATH=%P1%%P2%%P3%%P4%%P5%%P6%%P7%%P8%%P9%%P10%%P11%

Then I invoke the ResGen and al command, I am not sure how to make it in powershell.
Any suggestion? Thanks in advance.
